{{!--
  freestyle-modifier-advanced-reference.hbs — the advanced decomposition /
  operator-theory reference (body-modifier reference, intermediate operators,
  execution mechanics, set primitives). Rendered below the modifier feel cards in
  /freestyle/glossary §6, via the shared modifier-reference partial.

  Each operator appears on exactly one of these surfaces, so its term-{slug}
  anchor resolves to a single element: body modifiers in the body-modifier
  reference, decomposable set/compound operators in the intermediate-operators
  list, and Pixie / Fairy in the set-primitive grid (the only primitives whose
  term-anchor link target lives nowhere else).

  Required view-model fields on parent `content`:
    - intermediateOperators: OperatorReferenceEntry[]
    - setModifiers: FreestyleSetModifierEntry[]
    - tier1Definitions: Record<slug, string> — the canonical Tier-1 definition
      lines. Each body-modifier <dd> below renders its definition from this
      record and keeps only its per-term extras (formula, panel links, family
      notes) inline, so this partial never authors a competing definition.

  Anchors preserved verbatim (id="advanced-decomposition-operator-theory",
  id="modifier-reference", id="intermediate-operators", id="execution-mechanics",
  id="set-modifiers-tier-1", and per-entry `term-{slug}`).
--}}
<section class="glossary-advanced-reference-group">
  <h3 class="section-heading" id="advanced-decomposition-operator-theory">
    Advanced Decomposition &amp; Operator Theory
    <span class="glossary-tier-badge glossary-tier-badge--advanced">Advanced Reference</span>
  </h3>
  <p>
    Optional reference layer. Structural readings of the modifiers
    above plus the compositional vocabulary used in equivalence chains,
    formula derivations, and operational-notation analysis.
  </p>

  <h4 class="section-heading" id="modifier-reference">Body modifier reference</h4>
  <p>Structural definitions for the body-modifier cohort. The connective panels in &sect;9 surface each term's relationship to specific tricks.</p>
  <dl>
    <dt id="term-stepping">Stepping</dt>
    <dd>Stepping is launch / set vocabulary; see <a href="#section-timing-sets">Timing &amp; Sets</a>. Used compositionally, it modifies a base (stepping + butterfly = ripwalk).</dd>
    <dt id="term-paradox">Paradox</dt>
    <dd>
      {{content.tier1Definitions.paradox}}
      <span class="glossary-paradox-formula">Formula: <code class="notation-display-tokens"><span class="notation-token notation-modifier">PDX</span> &rarr; <span class="notation-token">CLIP</span> &gt; <span class="notation-token">OP IN</span> <span class="notation-token">[DEX]</span></code>:clipper set, then a far in-out dex.</span>
      <a href="#glossary-panel-paradox">See connective panel</a>.
    </dd>
    <dt id="term-spinning">Spinning</dt>
    <dd>{{content.tier1Definitions.spinning}} Pairs with gyro (180&deg;) for arbitrary degrees. <a href="#glossary-panel-spinning">See connective panel</a>.</dd>
    <dt>Ducking</dt>
    <dd>{{content.tier1Definitions.ducking}} One member of a four-way ducking family (ducking / weaving / diving / zulu): diving is the complement (the bag passes over the player), while weaving and zulu are ducking sets. <a href="#glossary-panel-ducking">See connective panel</a>.</dd>
    <dt id="term-symposium">Symposium</dt>
    <dd>{{content.tier1Definitions.symposium}} Often stacks with paradox (the &ldquo;PS X&rdquo; shorthand).</dd>
    <dt id="term-cross-body">Cross-body</dt>
    <dd>A general descriptor for tricks (and components) where the active foot or dex crosses the body's center line. ADD category XBD covers cross-body components.</dd>
  </dl>

  <details class="glossary-core-atom-collapsible">
    <summary>Advanced decomposition, execution mechanics, and set-modifier notation</summary>
    <p class="detail-muted">
      Structural proofs, execution detail, and set-modifier notation. For scoring
      weights and decomposition accounting see
      <a href="/freestyle/add-analysis">ADD Accounting &amp; Analysis</a>; for the
      set operational forms see the
      <a href="/freestyle/sets/reference">set notation reference</a>.
    </p>
  <h4 class="section-heading" id="intermediate-operators">Intermediate operators:decomposition reference</h4>
  <p>Operators that decompose into combinations of other operators and Tier-1 primitives. Each entry shows its one-line meaning, its semantic decomposition where known, and worked examples. A few readings are still being worked out. See also the <a href="/freestyle/sets/reference">set notation reference</a> for the operational forms these operators produce.</p>
  <p class="detail-muted">Entries tagged <span class="glossary-operator-nickname-flag">historical name</span> are legacy nickname naming patterns, not canonical sets of their own; they resolve to an official set (for example, Barraging resolves to the Furious set, and Miraging is descriptive standalone inward-movement language rather than the Quantum set).</p>
<dl class="glossary-intermediate-operators">
  {{#each content.intermediateOperators}}
  <dt id="term-{{slug}}">
    {{name}}
    {{#if isHistoricalNickname}}<span class="glossary-operator-nickname-flag" title="A historical nickname naming pattern, not a canonical set; resolves to an official set">historical name</span>{{/if}}
    {{#if curatorConfirmPending}}<span class="glossary-operator-pending-flag">pending</span>{{/if}}
  </dt>
  <dd>
    <p class="glossary-operator-meaning">{{oneLineMeaning}}</p>
    {{#if decomposition}}
    <p class="glossary-operator-decomposition"><span class="glossary-operator-decomposition-label">Decomposes as:</span> {{decomposition}}</p>
    {{/if}}
    {{#if pendingNote}}
    <p class="glossary-operator-pending-note">{{pendingNote}}</p>
    {{/if}}
    {{#if workedExamples.length}}
    <p class="glossary-operator-examples">{{#each workedExamples}}{{#unless @first}} &middot; {{/unless}}<em>{{this}}</em>{{/each}}</p>
    {{/if}}
    <p class="glossary-operator-lineage">{{lineageNote}}</p>
  </dd>
  {{/each}}
</dl>

<h3 class="section-heading" id="execution-mechanics">Execution mechanics</h3>
<p class="freestyle-section-sub">Mechanical details that operator names alone don't capture.</p>
<dl class="glossary-execution-mechanics">
  <dt id="term-alpine">Alpine</dt>
  <dd>Divides a trick between its uptime and downtime, inserting a duck or dive between them. Alpine Ripwalk = Stepping Ducking Butterfly.</dd>

  <dt id="term-symposium-mech">Symposium (mechanic)</dt>
  <dd>A component where an active leg performs an action in a single-leg jump: the symposium leg jumps and lands on its own while the other leg remains in the air.</dd>

  <dt id="term-symple">Symple</dt>
  <dd>Symposium is the established operator. Symple and the shorthand <em>symp</em> also appear in source material as historical tokens, but whether Symple names a distinct movement, and whether <em>symp</em> means anything beyond an abbreviation of Symposium, are unresolved.</dd>

  <dt id="term-muted">Muted</dt>
  <dd>An active leg held in the air for an entire component without planting. Mostly used for dexes, but applies to other components too.</dd>
</dl>

<h3 class="section-heading" id="set-modifiers-tier-1">Set modifiers (not core tricks)</h3>
<p>
  Set modifiers are structural treatments applied <em>to</em> a base
  trick, not bases themselves. See the
  <a href="/freestyle/sets/reference">set notation reference</a> for the full
  vocabulary.
</p>
<div class="glossary-set-modifiers-grid">
  {{#each content.setModifiers}}
  <article class="set-modifier-card" id="term-{{slug}}">
    <p class="set-modifier-head">
      <span class="set-modifier-name">{{name}}</span>
      {{#if glyph}}<span class="set-modifier-glyph">{{glyph}}</span>{{/if}}
    </p>
    <p class="set-modifier-meaning">{{oneLineMeaning}}</p>
    {{#if decomposition}}
    <p class="set-modifier-decomposition"><span class="set-modifier-decomp-sigil">&equiv;</span> {{decomposition}}</p>
    {{/if}}
    {{#if href}}
    <a class="set-modifier-deeplink" href="{{href}}" aria-label="Notation reference">&rarr;</a>
    {{/if}}
  </article>
  {{/each}}
</div>
  </details>
</section>
